Question 1

(50 points) Use numeric prediction techniques to build a predictive model for the HW3.xlsx dataset. This dataset is provided on the course website and contains data about whether or not different consumers made a purchase in response to a test mailing of a certain catalog and, in case of a purchase, how much money each consumer spent. The data file has a brief description of all the attributes in a separate worksheet. Note that this dataset has two possible outcome variables: Purchase (0/1 value: whether or not the purchase was made) and Spending (numeric value: amount spent).

Your tasks:

(a) (20 points) Build numeric prediction models that predict Spending based on the other available customer information (obviously, not including the Purchase attribute among the inputs!). Use linear regression, k-NN, regression tree, SVM regreesion and Neural Network and ensembling models. Briefly discuss your explorations and present the best result (best predictive model) for each of these techniques. Compare the techniques; which of them provides the best predictive performance? Please make sure you use best practices for predictive modeling. (I.e., do you need to set which hyper-parameter? Normalize?)

(b) (20 points) As a variation on this exercise, create a separate “restricted” dataset (i.e., a subset of the original dataset), which includes only purchase records (i.e., where Purchase = 1). Build numeric prediction models to predict Spending for this restricted dataset. All the same requirements as for task (a) apply.

(c) (10 points) For each predictive modeling technique, discuss the predictive performance differences between the models built for task (a) vs. task (b): which models exhibit better predictive performance? Why do you think that is?

Solution:¶

For the given problem, we make use of the following numeric prediction models and compare based on the least error. Throughout the modelling process, the workflow was as follows:

  1. Find the best split for the data
  2. Run a naive implementation of the model
  3. Use GridSearch CV to find out the best settings of the hyperparameters
  4. For Neural Networks a. We first start with a baseline model on an input and an output layer b. Then we make the model deeper by adding another layer of neurons c. We add one more layer of neurons to see how better is this deeper model compared to the previous one.

Based on the modeling done, we achieve the following results:
For part (a),

  1. Linear Regression | 136
  2. KNN Regression | Min. error = 150 | Max. R-squared = 0.23
  3. Support Vector Regression | Min. error ~ 200 | Max. R-sqaured = 0.23
  4. Regression Trees | Min. error ~ 150 | Max. R-squared = 0.53
  5. Neural Networks | Min. error ~ 124
  6. Ensemble Method (AdaBoost)| Min. error ~ 128 | Max. R-squared = 0.70

Thus, from the above figures, we see that the AdaBoost ensemble technique built on top of the regression trees helps to further explain the variation in the regression line (R-squared) as well as achieves a lower error). Thus, AdaBoost becomes our preferred model for this numeric prediction.

For part (b), we focus on the explanablility of the models and see how better or worse can our models explain the variation in the data. We see the following results:

  1. Linear Regression | Min. error ~ 175
  2. KNN Regression | Max. R-squared = 0.23
  3. Support Vector Regression | Max. R-sqaured = 0.05
  4. Regression Trees | Max. R-squared = 0.46
  5. Neural Networks | Min. error ~ 165
  6. Ensemble Method (AdaBoost)| Max. R-squared = 0.660

As can be seen from above, the AdaBoost ensemble method still provides the best predictive performance among all other models, followed by the regression trees.

Now, comparing part (a) to (b), we see that the modelling performance has gone down for all the models used in the dataset. One explanation for this is the removal of a column that would be influential in determining the Spending amount, "Purchase". A clear determiner of spending, Purchase column would give a sense of whether or not a purchase is acutally made and is therefore an important factor. When we remove Purchase = 1 rows from the dataset, we have removed the variation that could be explained by the features of Purchase column (i.e. the differet rows that correspond to either purchase = 1 or 0). Therefore, our models have to try higher to predict the spending amount and therefore perform worse than previous.

# Have to calculate Symmetric MAPE as multiple 0 values make the calculation Inf


def smape(A, F):
    return 100/len(A) * np.sum(2 * np.abs(F - A) / (np.abs(A) + np.abs(F)))


print("SMAPE : ",round(smape(pred, ytest),2))

# Iterate over multiple train - test splits to find the best possible for a random state

mae_score = []
mape_score = []
smape_score = []
rmse_score = []
r_score = []

test_size = list(range(10,35,2))
for size in test_size:
    xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(data.iloc[:,:-2], data['Spending'], 
                                                    random_state = 1234567890, test_size = size/100)

    # Regressor
    reg = LR().fit(xtrain, ytrain)

    #Predict 
    pred = reg.predict(xtest)

    #Absolute error (residuals)
    abs_err = pred - ytest
    abs_perr = pred/ytest -1
    
    print ("")
    print ("Test size : ", size/100)
    print ("---")
    
    # R-squared value
    print("R squared : ", round(reg.score(xtest, ytest),2))
    r_score.append(float(round(reg.score(xtest, ytest),2)))
    
    # Mean Absolute Error
    print ("MAE : ", round(np.mean(abs(abs_err)),2))
    mae_score.append(float(round(np.mean(abs(abs_err)),2)))
    
    # Mean Absolute Percentage Error
    print ("MAPE : ", round(np.mean(abs(abs_perr)),2))
    mape_score.append(float(round(np.mean(abs(abs_perr)),2)))
    
    #SMAPE
    print ("SMAPE : ",round(smape(pred, ytest),2))
    smape_score.append(float(round(smape(pred, ytest),2)))
    
    #RMSE
    print ("RMSE : ", round(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(pred, ytest)),2))
    rmse_score.append(float(round(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(pred, ytest)),2)))

# Iterate over multiple train - test splits to find the best possible for a random state

mae_score = []
mape_score = []
smape_score = []
rmse_score = []
r_score = []

test_size = list(range(10,35,2))
for size in test_size:
    xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(data.iloc[:,:-2], data['Spending'], 
                                                    random_state = 1234567890, test_size = size/100)

    # Regressor
    reg = KNR(n_neighbors = 10).fit(xtrain, ytrain)

    #Predict 
    pred = reg.predict(xtest)

    #Absolute error (residuals)
    abs_err = pred - ytest
    abs_perr = pred/ytest -1
    
    print ("")
    print ("Test size : ", size/100)
    print ("---")
    
    # R-squared value
    print("R squared : ", round(reg.score(xtest, ytest),2))
    r_score.append(float(round(reg.score(xtest, ytest),2)))
    
    # Mean Absolute Error
    print ("MAE : ", round(np.mean(abs(abs_err)),2))
    mae_score.append(float(round(np.mean(abs(abs_err)),2)))
    
    # Mean Absolute Percentage Error
    print ("MAPE : ", round(np.mean(abs(abs_perr)),2))
    mape_score.append(float(round(np.mean(abs(abs_perr)),2)))
    
    #SMAPE
    print ("SMAPE : ",round(smape(pred, ytest),2))
    smape_score.append(float(round(smape(pred, ytest),2)))
    
    #RMSE
    print ("RMSE : ", round(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(pred, ytest)),2))
    rmse_score.append(float(round(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(pred, ytest)),2)))

# Iterate over multiple train - test splits to find the best possible for a random state

mae_score = []
mape_score = []
smape_score = []
rmse_score = []
r_score = []

test_size = list(range(10,35,2))
for size in test_size:
    xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(data.iloc[:,:-2], data['Spending'], 
                                                    random_state = 1234567890, test_size = size/100)

    # Regressor
    reg = DTR().fit(xtrain, ytrain)

    #Predict 
    pred = reg.predict(xtest)

    #Absolute error (residuals)
    abs_err = pred - ytest
    abs_perr = pred/ytest -1
    
    print ("")
    print ("Test size : ", size/100)
    print ("---")
    
    # R-squared value
    print("R squared : ", round(reg.score(xtest, ytest),2))
    r_score.append(float(round(reg.score(xtest, ytest),2)))
    
    # Mean Absolute Error
    print ("MAE : ", round(np.mean(abs(abs_err)),2))
    mae_score.append(float(round(np.mean(abs(abs_err)),2)))
    
    # Mean Absolute Percentage Error
    print ("MAPE : ", round(np.mean(abs(abs_perr)),2))
    mape_score.append(float(round(np.mean(abs(abs_perr)),2)))
    
    #SMAPE
    print ("SMAPE : ",round(smape(pred, ytest),2))
    smape_score.append(float(round(smape(pred, ytest),2)))
    
    #RMSE
    print ("RMSE : ", round(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(pred, ytest)),2))
    rmse_score.append(float(round(math.sqrt(mean_squared_error(pred, ytest)),2)))

def larger_model():
    # create model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(23, input_dim=23, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(10, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='normal'))
    # Compile model
    model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')
    return model

def larger_model():
    # create model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(23, input_dim=23, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(12, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(6, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='normal'))

    return model

params = []
for max_depth in range(1,20):
    for criterion in ['mae', 'mse']:
        for loss in ['linear','square' ,'exponential']:
            for estimators in [5,10,15]:
                xtrain, xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(data.iloc[:,:-2], data['Spending'], test_size = 0.26)
                model = AdaBoostRegressor(base_estimator  = DTR(criterion=criterion, max_depth=max_depth, max_features=None, 
                                                 max_leaf_nodes=None, min_impurity_decrease=0.0, 
                                                 min_impurity_split=None, min_samples_leaf=1, 
                                                 min_samples_split=2, min_weight_fraction_leaf=0.0, 
                                                 presort=False, random_state=None, splitter='best'), 
                              n_estimators = estimators, loss = loss)
                model.fit(xtrain, ytrain)                
                model_score.append(model.score(xtest, ytest))            
                params.append((max_depth, criterion, loss, estimators))

b. Cost Sensitive Approach¶

For the cost sensitive approach, our trigger is that the average misclassification cost should be minimized by given higher priority to the False Positives and we attach at 10x cost for every misclassification done to predict a Non Spam email as a Spam. We therefore focus on scoring the models by Precision and determine the best models from it.

Conclusions from classifcation of emails

In this problem, our task is to classify the emails into Spam or Not Spam using the 57 given attributes in 4600+ records. We first normalize the data (all columns), so that all are between 0 and 1 using a MinMaxScaler.

We took two approaches to determine the best performing classifiers for the email spam filtering problem. In the first case, we assumed an equal cost weight for misclassifications of Non spam into spam and vice versa. In the second case, we assigned a greater weight to the first misclassification (The False Positives) in our predictions of 10x.

This translated to looking for higher Precision model, such that we minimize the number of False Positive in our predictions.

The models tested to find the best predictive performance include : Decision Tree, Logistic Regression, Support Vector Machines, K-Nearest Neighbors, Ensemble Technique - Random Forest and Neural Network.

In the first approach (Cost insensitive approach) , we see that Random Forest model achieves the highest accuracy out of all the models tested with 96%. The next best predictive performance is achieved by Logistic Regression Classifier with 92.9% accuracy, followed closely by our perceptron neural network model at 92%. KNN classifier gave the worst performance with 82% accuracy.

When we take misclassification cost into account, we find that the predictive performance follows a similar order, with Random Forest having the lowest misclassification cost of 56. However, in this case, SVM appears to be performing the worst with a misclassification cost of 392 on the test data.

This leads us to believe that accuracy and the equal costed model showcase a similar behavior.

Part (a) Summary¶

Summary Scores (Accuracy):

  • Random Forest : 0.96
  • Logistic Regression : 0.929
  • Neural Network : 0.92
  • Decision Tree Classifier : 0.916
  • SVM : 0.869
  • KNN : 0.820

Misclassification Cost from different models:

  • Random Forest : 56
  • Logistic Regression : 92
  • Neural Networks : 104
  • Decsison Tree : 115
  • KNN : 239
  • SVM : 392

In the second approach (Cost sensitive with 10:1), we added a 10x weight to the cost matrix achieved after the predictive modelling for each classifier and found out the misclassification cost.

We observed that, all the models had a significantly higher misclassfication cost compared to the previous approach. This is due to the amount of cost added for each misclassification. However, even in this approch, we are able to achieve the best predictive performance from the Random Forest ensemble classifier, both in terms of Misclassification cost (329) and predictive accuracy (0.97).

A slightly strange observation is with regards to the SVM classifier, in that, it has the second lowest cost of 400, but the lowest accuracy of just 71%. Such a behavior is observed, because while optimizing the model for precision score, the SVM classifier optimized for one of the two classes (Spam = 1) and achieved a 100% Precision for filtering all those emails which are spam correctly. However, its performance drops significantly when considering the other class (Spam = 0), as it has a precision of only 68%. Therefore, we should be careful while choosing our model as SVM classifier for this kind of email filtering problem with imbalances weights.
